{
  "doc_id": "33610",
  "text": "Gene location impacts sex bias in D. melanogaster: there are reports of fewer male-biased genes on the X chromosome [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Similarly, for our set of D. simulans genotypes, we find more female-biased genes relative to male-biased genes on the X relative to the autosomes (table 2; w 2 : P < 0.0001). For X-linked genes, sex differences in transcript abundance may result either via the sex determination pathway (e.g., downstream of fru and dsx; [CITATION_3] or from dosage compensation [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] ; while for genes on autosomes, differences in transcript abundance between the sexes are expected to result solely from the sex determination pathway (trans variation via sex determination, or cis variation in the binding sites for dsx, etc.).",
